You said:
oh shit with media pipe, is it able to run on M4? 
ChatGPT said:
Yes! MediaPipe runs perfectly on Apple Silicon (M1, M2, M3, M4) Macs, including the M4 chip.

Here’s why:

MediaPipe is mostly written in C++ with cross-platform support (via Bazel).

Prebuilt AARs (for Android) and Python wheels (for Mac/Linux/Windows) are available.

Apple Silicon is fully supported — you can even build MediaPipe from source with native ARM64 acceleration if needed.

If you’re using it via Android Studio, it doesn’t even run on your Mac — it compiles into your Android app (so your Mac’s CPU/GPU don’t matter, except for builds).

For Local Testing on Mac
If you want to run MediaPipe natively on macOS (e.g., testing Face Mesh with Python), there are ARM64 wheels:

pip install mediapipe
This will run on M1/M2/M3/M4 without Rosetta.

