ChatGPT said:
Ah, I see the problem — this crash is not about M4 compatibility but likely due to MediaPipe using precompiled native code (JNI) that doesn’t play well with your Android emulator or specific ABI settings. Let me break it down:

Why This Happens
MediaPipe's Android AARs come with native C++ libraries (libmediapipe_jni.so) built for certain ABIs (armeabi-v7a, arm64-v8a).

If your emulator is running x86_64 (most emulators do by default), MediaPipe doesn’t have x86_64 binaries, leading to crashes like SIGILL (illegal instruction).

On real Android devices (ARM), this error typically doesn’t occur.

Fixes
Use an ARM Emulator Image
When creating your Android emulator in AVD Manager:

Choose "ARM64" or "ARM" system image instead of x86/x86_64.

These will be slower since they run via QEMU, but MediaPipe will work.

Run on a Real Device (Recommended)

MediaPipe hand/face tracking is GPU-heavy and will be much smoother on a physical phone.

Add ABI Filters in build.gradle
Ensure your app is only built with ARM libraries:

android {
 defaultConfig {
 ndk {
 abiFilters "armeabi-v7a", "arm64-v8a"
 }
 }
}
Check Camera Permissions
Your log has:

Operation not started: uid=10216 pkg=com.example.finger_drawing(null) op=CAMERA
Make sure you added:

<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.CAMERA" />
And requested camera permission at runtime for Android 6.0+.

TL;DR
MediaPipe is fine on M4 Macs (for building), but your x86 emulator crashes because MediaPipe doesn’t ship x86 binaries.

Either switch emulator to ARM64 or run on a physical Android device.

Want me to give you a step-by-step guide to create an ARM64 emulator in Android Studio that works with MediaPipe?



