# Building Android Applications with MediaPipe’s Graph-Based Pipeline
[](/@shahin.cse.sust?source=post_page---byline--ed1b74768183---------------------------------------)[Shahinoor Shahin](/@shahin.cse.sust?source=post_page---byline--ed1b74768183---------------------------------------)4 min read·Jun 11, 2025[
](/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fvote%2Fp%2Fed1b74768183&operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F%40shahin.cse.sust%2Fbuilding-android-applications-with-mediapipes-graph-based-pipeline-ed1b74768183&user=Shahinoor+Shahin&userId=f4e0319da31&source=---header_actions--ed1b74768183---------------------clap_footer------------------)--

[](/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fbookmark%2Fp%2Fed1b74768183&operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F%40shahin.cse.sust%2Fbuilding-android-applications-with-mediapipes-graph-based-pipeline-ed1b74768183&source=---header_actions--ed1b74768183---------------------bookmark_footer------------------)Share

MediaPipe is an open-source framework developed by Google for building multimodal (video, audio, and sensor) applied machine learning pipelines. Its graph-based architecture makes it particularly powerful for Android developers looking to integrate complex media processing and machine learning capabilities into their applications.

# Prerequisites
Before we begin, make sure you have:

- Android Studio installed (latest version recommended)
- Basic knowledge of Android development (Java/Kotlin)
- Familiarity with protobuf (Protocol Buffers) is helpful but not required
- A device or emulator running Android 5.0 (API level 21) or higher

# Setting Up MediaPipe for Android

## 1. Install Bazel

MediaPipe uses Bazel as its build system. Install Bazel on your development machine:

```
# On macOSbrew install bazel# On Linuxsudo apt install bazel# On Windows (via Chocolatey)choco install bazel
```

# 2. Clone the MediaPipe Repository

```
git clone https://github.com/google/mediapipe.gitcd mediapipe
```
