ChatGPT said:
Got it — let's focus on detecting a horizontal open hand so you can position fire above it.

Detecting a Horizontal Open Hand
1. Finger Extension Check
First, ensure the hand is open:

Compute the distance between fingertip landmarks (8, 12, 16, 20) and their MCP joints (5, 9, 13, 17).

If these distances are large enough (relative to palm size), the hand is considered open.

2. Palm Orientation
We want to detect if the palm is facing up (horizontal).

Compute the palm normal vector using landmarks:

Use wrist (0), index base (5), and pinky base (17) to form a plane.

The cross product of (5 - 0) and (17 - 0) gives the normal vector.

If the z-component of this normal vector is negative and its magnitude is high (e.g., abs(normal[2]) > some_threshold), the palm is likely facing the camera (horizontal and upward).

3. Fire Position
The fire should be drawn at the center of the palm, which can be approximated as the average of the points [0, 5, 9, 13, 17].

Scale and place your fire animation relative to this point.

Kotlin Pseudo-Logic for Android
kotlin
Copy
Edit
fun isPalmUpOpen(handLandmarks: List<Point3D>): Boolean {
 val wrist = handLandmarks[0]
 val indexBase = handLandmarks[5]
 val pinkyBase = handLandmarks[17]

 // 1. Finger extension check
 val fingersExtended = listOf(8 to 5, 12 to 9, 16 to 13, 20 to 17).all { (tip, base) ->
 distance(handLandmarks[tip], handLandmarks[base]) > 0.05f
 }

 if (!fingersExtended) return false

 // 2. Palm normal
 val v1 = indexBase - wrist
 val v2 = pinkyBase - wrist
 val normal = crossProduct(v1, v2)

 // 3. Check if palm is facing camera (z < 0)
 return normal.z < -0.1f
}

fun palmCenter(handLandmarks: List<Point3D>): Point3D {
 val indices = listOf(0, 5, 9, 13, 17)
 return indices.map { handLandmarks[it] }
 .reduce { acc, p -> acc + p } / indices.size.toFloat()
}
